##Prison riot in Italy, 20 escape, 7 dead

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Nan Boyi, _ the_paper _ reporter

On March 9, riots broke out in Italian prisons in protest against the Italian government's epidemic prevention measures. The riot resulted in the escape of 20 prisoners and the death of seven.

According to a report by the Agenzia Nazionale Stampa Associata on March 9, a total of 50 prisoners escaped from Foggia prison in southern Italy during the riot on the morning of March 9. Meanwhile, fires broke out in two prisons in the capital, Rome, and a prison in Province of Prato following a prisoner uprising.

Seven prisoners have been killed in prison riots across Italy, including those who died from an overdose of psychotropic drugs and those who died from choking on fire fumes.

According to the US newspaper Business Insider, as the Italian government announced on the 8th that the northern part of the country would be sealed off, prisoners in the prison also felt restricted after the Italian emergency closure was reported, because the closure of the city has affected visits by prisoners'families. In addition, because the prison is a closed space, the inmates of the new coronavirus infection panic, which led to riots.

According to the Agenzia Nazionale Stampa Associata, there were serious disturbances at San Vittore prison in Milan and Rebibia prison in Rome, with inmates setting mattresses on fire and attacking the infirmary. The worst of the rioting took place at Pavia prison, south of Milan, where inmates vandalised facilities and were persuaded to return to their cells after "long and difficult negotiations" with prison officials.

Italy's prison system can accommodate about 51,000 prisoners, but there are now more than 61,000 in active service, which is long term intensive.

Alfonso Bonafede, Italy's justice minister, said he would brief the Senate Wednesday at 5 p.m. urgently on the prison riots.
